An excellent diſcourſe called the Metamorphoſis of old Iack Vaughan; with the Dialogue between him &..... a worthy Commoner, who meeting old Vaughan in Weſtminſter-Hall, ſaluted him with many congratulations, wishing him joy of his Court-preferments; to which old Vaughan replyed, Do you not ſee my grey-hairs? Alas, Alas, I am too old to be a Knave; the Court may deſign what they pleas, but they miſtake the Man, I am reſolued never to quit the Commons jntereſt: Yet with 6. hours this old man turned young, & nimbly skipp'd to White-hall, where he made a Coupee, and from honeſt old Iack became Sr. Iohn, & with the Courant-figure became Serjeant Iohn, & with a Caper leapt into the Chief-Iuſtice ſeat in the Common-pleas; & is become an Excellent Dancer after a Court-horn-pipe; which cauſed one to ſend him theſe 2. lines to paint in his Coat of Arms,


This is no wonder in ſuch a Man;

One honeſt Lawyer shew who can?
